<center><h3><a name=aa1>DOLE: "Just Cut Out the Advertising"</a></h3></a></center></h3>


New York, NY July 5, 1996. Little noticed by most during Wednesday's Katie Couric interview was presidential contender Bob Dole's suggestion to "[j}ust cut out the advertising" of cigarettes.

<p>The statement's implications may have been lost on reporters already shocked by Dole's suggestions that Couric may be violating FCC rules by "advertising" Democratic positions, or that conservative ex-Surgeon General C. Everett Koop may have been "a little bit" brainwashed by the liberal media. The idea of banning all cigarette advertising, coming from a government-hands-off politician, may well have been an unfortunate misstatement, as such a sweeping proposal seems to go far beyond anything the FDA or President Clinton has yet suggested.

<p>In full, Dole said to Couric on a segment of NBC's "Today" which had been taped Sunday but aired Wednesday morning:

<blockquote>Cigarettes aren't good for you. I voted for tougher smoking laws as far as giving it back to the states. States ought to handle it. I don't have any quarrel with it. Just cut out the advertising, do all the other things. But it is legal.</blockquote>

<p>It was unclear what Dole was referring to when he said, "do all the other things."

<p>The Washington, DC-based Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids immediately issued a press release which states that the organization 

<blockquote>...applauds Sen. Dole's groundbreaking statement yesterday endorsing a ban on tobacco advertising . . . [H]is statement makes clear that he recognizes that tobacco advertising increases the use of tobacco products by young people. . .

<p>While some people are saying that we should trust the tobacco industry to regulate their own advertising, we agree with Sen. Dole that it is better to "just cut out the advertising.</blockquote>

<center><h3><a name=aa2>Teens to Protest Ticketmaster/Joe Camel Promotion</a></h3></center></a>

Seattle, WA. May 2, 1996. Teen tobacco-control groups today announced that on Saturday they will protest Ticketmaster's participation in RJ Reynolds' Joe Camel "Rockin' Road Trip." The "Road Trip" is a promotional campaign in which Ticketmaster offers gift certificates to rock concerts for "Camel Cash," coupons obtainable from Camel cigarette packs

<p>The teens' protest will start at 1PM on Pine St., outside the Westlake Center Ticketmaster outlet in downtown Seattle. Participating groups include REACT, SMOOTH and ALERT.

<center><h3><a name=aa3>CA: Pols to Guide Scientific Research</a></h3></a></center></h3>

Sacramento, CA. July 3, 1996. The tortured history California's Proposition 99 (1988) cigarette tax funds--which at one time found the California Medical Association fighting side-by-side with tobacco interests and Governor Pete Wilson to redirect them--took another bizarre turn today. State budget negotiators have agreed to allow political appointees to approve or disapprove research funded with the $60 million the tax brings in for tobacco research and education.

<p>HOW THE POLITICAL REVIEW WOULD WORK

<p>The University of California, which has previously overseen the funds and assigned research based on a peer-review process, would prepare a spending plan for the Department of Finance. A governor-appointed Tobacco Education Research Oversight Committee would then conduct public hearings and make recommendations.

<p>The budget provision was backed by new Assembly Speaker Curt Pringle (R-Garden Grove), who last week attached another provision specifically forbidding the state Department of Health Services's TV ads from attacking the tobacco industry.

<p>According to a UC study, Pringle has received $25,250 in tobacco contributions since 1993. A spokesperson said Pringle was "philosophically opposed to using taxpayer dollars to attack any industry."

<p>REACTION

<p>The research community was in an uproar, partly because UC said they would accept the plan. A UC spokesperson said he saw no major change in how UC approved research, and that he could understand how the state would want to keep close tabs on the allocation of so much money.

<p>One UC researcher could be particularly hard-hit by the provision: Dr. Stanton Glantz, a scientist whose research has often rebutted industry claims, and who is considered by many to be the tobacco industry's worst enemy. Glantz was the target of a federal-level scientific de-funding effort last year. "But this goes way beyond me," he said. "This is an outrageous intrusion into the scientific and academic process. I cannot imagine a clearer intrusion into the academic freedom of a university."

<center><h3><a name=aa4>MA: Bill Would require Disclosure of "The List"</a></h3></a></center></h3>

July 26, 1996. Boston, MA. Gov. Weld has said he will sign an unprecedented bill which would require cigarette manufacturers to reveal the "recipes"--added ingredients and their amounts--of each brand of cigarette. The result of the bill, passed by the Senate 39-0 last Thursday (7/25/96), may be public disclosure of "The List" of cigarette additives for the first time in history.

<p>Though manufacturers revealed their additives to the government in 1994, they were allowed to present a compiled list of 599--with no brands or amounts specified. In addition, the list was kept secret from the public.

<p>The Tolman bill (Sen. Warren Tolman, D-Waterford is chief sponsor) would require manufacturers to present their information to the Mass. Department of Public Health, which could then release the list to the public.

<p><i>Every food and every drug has to list its ingredients and tobacco products will now be held to the same standard,</i> Tolman said.

<center><h3><a name=aa5>MA: Weld Signs Tobacco Ingredient Disclosure Law</a></h3></a></center></h3>

Boston, MA. August 2, 1996. Gov. Weld signed the <a href="http://www.jointogether.org/news/jto/Show_News.qry?News_uid=8392">Tolman bill</a> at a news conference. The law will take effect in 3 months. Meanwhile, even as the conference was being held, tobacco companies were filing suit to overturn the law, charging that federal labeling regulations preempt state provisions, and that the  law would force them to disclose trade secrets.

<center><h3><a name=aaramsey>MN: Airline Gives Free Flights To Clerks Passing Compliance Tests</a></h3></a></center></h3>

<li>RAMSEY COUNTY, MN. May 20, 1996 Clerks who pass compliance checks conducted by the North Suburban Tobacco Compliance Project will get a chance to win two round-trip tickets - donated by Northwest Airlines - to anywhere in the continental United States. Chances of winning are pretty good--last fall, 153 clerks passed, and 53 failed.

<center><h3><a name=aa6>ENGLAND: BAT Chief Wins Cambridge Chair Fight</a></h3></a></center></h3>

After a 6-month ethical brouhaha, Cambridge University's parliamentary body approved by a 2-1 margin (1,128 to 583) a L1.6 million donation by tobacco giant BAT Industries Plc. Accompanying the donation is a chair in international relations named for BAT's former chairman, Sir Patrick Sheehy.

<p>Approached by the press as a battle between idealists and pragmatists, the furor--which pitted academic titans against each other--was sparked by Cambridge's creation of a Sir Patrick Sheehy Chair in international relations last February. Opponents--including the University's senior medical academic, <p>Sir Keith Peters--objected to accepting money from, and honoring the chairman of, a tobacco company.

<p>Oxford recently set up an ethics committee to screen donations. Cambridge, instead, sent out a postal ballot to 3,300 dons and senior administrators.

<p>In defense of the donation, Sir Roger Tomkys, master of Pembroke College, said, <i>I respect the ethical hesitations by some senior members of the university but this new chair will not sell a single cigarette. . . If you examine the business morality of every commercial organization, there is no clean money out there. You can't take money from the arms trade, from the pharmaceutical industry because of animal experiments, or from the banks because of their Third World policies.</i>

<p>Some of the arguments that were made against the donation: 

<blockquote><p><li><i>Cambridge University has sold its good name to a company which profits from sales of a lethal and highly-addictive product. The university will inevitably be used by BAT to promote tobacco in its developing world markets.</i>--Pamela Furness, chief executive of ASH

<p><li><i>We wouldn't accept money from Saddam Hussein to set up a chair in Arabic studies.</i>--Professor Nick Davies, director of the Institute of Public Health

<p><li><i>BAT kill half their regular customers so they have to spend a lot of money buying goodwill.</i> --Professor Richard Peto, Imperial Cancer Research Fund.</blockquote>

<p>A spokesperson for BAT said, <i>The idea that we are trying to buy respectability is laughable. We are one of the UK's top 10 companies.</i>

<p>BAT is the second-largest cigarette manufacturer in the world behind Philip Morris, and is the UK manufacturer of Benson & Hedges, Silk Cut and Lucky Strike brands.

<p>Sheehy was banned from the US this week in a separate matter involving Sherritt International, a Canadian mining company the State Department said had confiscated US property in Cuba. Under a new controversial US law meant to punish abuses in Cuba, Sheehy and several other directors have been notified they are banned from the US.

<center><h3><a name=aa10>Maxwell to Chair WPP?</a></h3></a></center></h3>

London, England. July 15, 1996. Hamish Maxwell, who steered Philip Morris' expanding fortunes in the 1980s, is expected to take over as Chairman of <a href="http://www.hillandknowlton.com/public/wpp.htm "> WPP Group PLC,</a> the world's largest advertising and marketing group, according to the Times of London.

<p>WPP owns giant advertising agencies Ogilvy & Mather and J. Walter Thompson and one-time tobacco PR firm Hill and Knowlton.

<p>Maxwell oversaw PM's expansion into international markets, and its acquisition of General Foods and Kraft, creating one of the world's giant conglomerates. He is still chairman of PM's powerful executive committee, 

<center><h3><a name=aa7>FRANCE: PM "Milk" Ad Banned</a></h3></a></center>

Paris, France. June 27, 1996 A French court, ruling on a case brought by 77 cookie and cracker manufacturers, banned Philip Morris's ad campaign which implied that second-hand smoke was less dangerous than milk or biscuits. The court could fine PM US$200,000 for each infraction of France's advertising regulations.

<p>A "shocked and surprised" Philip Morris said it would immediately appeal the decision, but that the campaign's purpose--its third major effort to hold back EU tobacco control legislation--had been served. "We feel that we have got our message out."

<p>The court banned the ads because:
--advertising of tobacco products is illegal --comparative advertising is illegal
--advertising of tobacco products is "very harmful" (an echo of the phraseology of France's required health warnings) to the interests of biscuit makers

<p>"You don't need to use cookies to sell tobacco," said the lawyer for the cookie makers, but a European PM spokesperson said, "We're comparing scientific studies, not products."

<p>The company said, "The biscuit industry . . ., should not be trying . . . to suppress public awareness and discussion -- they should be joining with us in the effort to make the public aware of the dangers of misinterpretation of scientific studies."

<p>The print ad campaign was launched June 9 in European Union countries. The campaign cites certain studies to indicate that second hand smoke risks are less than the risks of drinking milk or chlorinated water, eating a biscuit a day, or peppering one's food. Tobacco control advocates and some European officials claim the ads are misleading, and do not address the risks of respiratory diseases and infections in children.

<p>A suit brought by Belgian biscuit makers who hold "the ads are defaming" was denied last Friday, but the suit will return to the courts this week. Italy and Holland are also looking into advertising code violations.

<center><h3><a name=aa8>ROMANIA: Cig Prices Skyrocket After Anti-smuggling Measures</a></h3></a></center>

Bucharest, Romania. May 8, 1996. Cigarette prices in Romania have increased 40% on the heels of the government's new anti-smuggling drive.

<p>Arrests of smuggling kingpins--one was alleged to be responsible for fully 1/5 of all cigarettes consumed in this heavy-smoking nation--and the institution of a new tax stamp program on May 1 have led to a severe cigarette shortage.

<p>Much of the problem has to do with delays in supplying foreign vendors with the stamps which verify origin and certify that customs fees--up to 300%--have been paid. The stamps are pink for local brands, green for imported.

<p>American brands have all but disappeared from retailers' shelves, but can be found later at night, stampless, at up to 3 times their normal prices.

<p>Romania has been known for having extremely low cigarette prices. Current prices for a pack of US or UK cigarettes range from US$1-$2. The average weekly salary in Romania is US$25.

<p>One third of adult Romanians smoke, and the country is Eastern Europes 2nd largest consumer of cigarettes behind Poland.

<center><h3><a name=aa9>ROMANIA: RJR Gives Health Warnings</a></h3></a></center>

Bucharest, Romania. June 11, 1996. RJR has voluntarily begun slapping its own health warnings on packs of its Romanian-produced brands--even though such warnings are not required by the government, according to Reuters.

<p>"Giving up smoking now considerably reduces the risk to your health" read the warnings, which are located on the side of brands produced in RJR's Bucharest factory, and are "tiny," Reuters says.

<p>Gerard Cayla, RJR general manager for Romania told Reuters, "We have been the first to put them on, as a token of respect for Romanian consumers."

<p>Romania has few restrictions on advertising and sale of cigarettes, but lately the cigarette market has been affecting national concerns in other ways.

<p>The government recently issued a tax stamp system to control rampant smuggling, but snafus led to a severe shortage of smuggled foreign cigarettes, and skyrocketing prices for local brands. 

<p>In fact, the ruling Social Democrats party blamed its recent heavy losses in a recent round of elections on cigarette price-gouging by retailers. The government responded by immediately instituting a price ceiling for cigarettes--at about half the going street prices--and hopes to do better in the next round of local elections this Sunday.

<p>"The Romanian Tobacco Authority will set retail prices . . . to eliminate the incorrect behavior of some traders ahead of the elections," said an official.

<center><h3><a name=aa11>POLAND: New Smoking Restrictions Take Effect</a></h3></center></a>

Warsaw, Poland. May 1, 1996. Poland's sweeping new smoking restrictions went into effect today. Smoking is now allowed only in designated smoking areas in many public places, including workplaces, hospitals, schools, and sports centers.

<p>Tobacco advertising is no longer allowed on TV and radio, in cinemas, youth and children's publications, hospitals, schools and sports centers or events. The sale of single cigarettes in vending machines or to those under 18 is now against the law.

<p>The bill authorizing the restrictions had once contained a total advertising ban, but the provision was considered harmful to publishers and to Poland's own plans to privatize the industry.

<p>The loosened advertising restrictions led Premier Lech Walesa to try to veto the bill last December, just before he left office. "The ambitious goal of the bill will not be reached if even a limited possibility of advertising tobacco remains," he said.

<center><h3><a name=aa12>PHILIPPINES: Supreme Court Lets Tan Off Tax Charges</a></h3></a></center>

Manila, The Philippines. June 4, 1996

<p>Amid charges that judges were "very lavishly bribed," the Supreme Court ruled the government had improperly prosecuted beer and tobacco magnate Lucio Tan and 67 officers of Fortune Tobacco Company for tax evasion.

<p>The decision deeply displeased president Fidel Ramos, who has been working towards tax reform.

<p>The charges against the three judges were made in a public letter from an unauthenticated group called "Crusade Against Corruption in the Supreme Court," and shook the country. In a rare statement, the Supreme Court condemned the  'poison pen letter' and its "cowardly and devious author." The statement called the charges "extremely vicious, scurrilous, false and malicious, libelous, unfair, baseless, mere `matters of guesswork,' the product of a malevolent mind. . . The Court declares its full support of and continuing confidence in these three members." Even government prosecutors excoriated the letter.

<p>Within days of the letter's release, the 3 accused judges--Santiago Kapunan, Josue Bellosillo and Regino Hermosisima--ruled for Tan in a 3-2 decision; in the decision, one judge called the government's task force, which had been set up to prosecute Tan, a "dictatorial technique."

<p>One of the dissenting judges wrote an unusually harsh critique. "I will have no part in the shocking process, especially in light of the fact that the government cries out that the people have been cheated and defrauded of their taxes to the tune of allegedly 25.6 billion pesos, and yet it is not given by this court even a beggar's chance to prove it," wrote Teodoro Padilla.

<p>The decision severely cripples the government's tax-reform and anti-corruption drive, which could threaten the country's recent economic gains.

<p>Tan, a Chinese immigrant who first worked as a janitor, is one of the richest men in the Philippines, worth an estimated $7 billion. Besides Fortune Tobacco, he owns Asia Brewery, and controls Philippine Airlines.


<center><h3><a name=aabeijing>BEIJING, CHINA. May 20, 1996. Beijing's ban on public smoking went into effect today.</a></h3></a></center>

<center><h3><a name=aa13>ZIMBABWE: Tobacco Exports Threatened by Child Labor Protest</a></h3></a></center>

Harare, Zimbabwe. May 16, 1996. "A major importer of our tobacco has threatened to stop dealing with us because of the issue of child labor on our farms,"  a senior government official told COMTEX today.

<p>At issue are child labor provisions among 176 labor-oriented basic human rights conventions, which the International Labour Organisation is requesting countries to ratify. Zimbabwe has ratified 6.

<p>The ILO defines child labor as denying a child education, or assigning labor that interferes with the child's basic development. An ILO official told COMTEX the organization was lenient with developing countries, but that the child labor issue "is very important to us."

<p>The official told COMTEX that farmers do provide schooling for children, who are often in the fields to "supplement family incomes." The lack of ratification could affect all Zimbabwe exports, but tobacco could hurt the country most.

<p>Zimbabwe is the world's third largest producer of flue-cured tobacco, next to Brazil and the United States. Tobacco is one of Zimbabwe's major exports, accounting for about 30 percent of total export earnings. It is also the single largest foreign currency earner, and is expected to bring in $700 million this year.

<p>50% of Zimbabwean tobacco is exported to the European Union, 20% to the Far East, and 10% to the United States.

<center><h3><a name=aa14>ZIMBABWE: 10% Tobacco Levy Passed</a></h3></a></center>

Harare, Zimbabwe. May 30, 1996. The Zimbabwe Parliament today approved a 10% tobacco levy, to be divided equally between growers and merchants.

<p>The unexpectedly high levy was pushed through by amendments to a less burdensome proposal by President Robert Mugabe's ZANU-PF party. Mugabe is expected to sign the bill.</p>

<p>The Zimbabwe Tobacco Association said the levy represented a double taxation, and could undermine Zimbabwe's position as the world's third largest tobacco producer behind the United States and Brazil. </p>

<p>Zimbabwe has had tough tobacco sales for the last 9 years, due to bad rains and some worldwide tobacco gluts.</p>

<p>This year, because of good rains during Zimbabwe's growing season (Nov. to March), tobacco is expected to bring in US$700 million, over three times the income of previous years. The levy would cost the industry some US$61.1 million.</p>

<p>The levy was also criticized as being especially harmful to black tobacco farmers, who generally own smaller farms.</p>

<center><h3><a name=aa15>A&P Removes Vending Machines</a></h3></a></center></h3>


Montvale, NJ. July 11, 1996. The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company announced today that it would remove all cigarette vending machines from its supermarkets by the end of July.

<p>A&P chairman and chief executive officer James Wood said, "We are in full support of President Clinton's effort to reduce the use of tobacco among young people."

<p>The 1,000-store chain also has instituted an age identification training videotape for cashiers, a lock-out software program that makes it impossible for tobacco products to be scanned at checkout counters without confirmation of the customer's age, and employee compliance checks at all stores.

<center><h3><a name=pmproposals>Tobacco Industry Proposes Youth Access Curbs</a></h3></a></center>
May 15, 1996. Attempting to preempt FDA regulation PHILIP MORRIS AND US TOBACCO sent a series of proposals to control youth access to tobacco. Tobacco control advocates were unimpressed, saying the provisions in practise amounted to a "stunt.". The White House said it was "somewhat encouraged and slightly disappointed." Notably absent from participation were R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp., and Lorillard Tobacco Co.

<center><h3><a name=aa16>Smoking is Good ???</a></h3></a>

<i> by Jeanne Scott (70673.3250@compuserve.com) </i></center>

<p>May 7,1 996. Under the header, "Making a Case for Death," the New York Times this week studied smoking's costs to society, including economic studies that claim to demonstrate the "inconvenient truth ... that smokers cover their own medical costs, not only by paying cigarette taxes ... but also by dying before collecting their full share of health and retirement benefits."

<p>Supporting such an argument at the very least raises several questions, including:  "How do we calculate what smokers cost everybody else?  Should we acknowledge that sometimes death is helpful to the public treasury?  And if that's so, where might such an argument end?"

<p>Two economic studies purport to show that smokers more than pay for the health costs they incur.  A Rand Corp. study conducted by University of Minnesota health economist Willard Manning showed that while smokers have higher health costs and died earlier than nonsmokers, society comes "out ahead" financially when the taxes they pay are figured into the equation.  A second study conducted by Duke University economist W. Kip Viscusi "found that smokers subsidize nonsmokers even without taxes."  After considering the savings in retirement benefits and nursing home costs that result from smokers' earlier deaths, Viscusi concluded that each pack of cigarettes sold in the U.S. results in a five cents "net gain to society."   In particular, he found that smoking provides "big savings" in retirement benefits -- up to $30 billion per year in pension costs are saved because many smokers die at an earlier age and cannot collect all of their benefits.

<p>[Note, this study is criticized because it did not factor in survivor's benefits and the costs to society of families losing a parent and relying more on social services to fill the gap.]

<p>Manhattan Institute for Policy Research Senior Fellow Peter Huber said, "Killing yourself by smoking incurs costs. ... But there are offsets.  It's quite possible that smokers are doing us all a small favor.  It's a ghoulish argument -- it's horrible -- but if you're going to have an economic case, you've got to use economics.  You can't use sentiment."

<p>Congressional Research Service economists Jane Gravelle and Dennis Zimmerman write that "the alternative to death from a smoking-related illness is not immortality and perfect health -- it is later death, and perhaps from a more costly illness."

<p>The Manning and Viscusi findings have their critics, many of whom cite Centers for Disease Control and Prevention data that show smoking's costs to be "several times higher." Others are bothered by the overall argument about smoking's costs to society.  MIT economist Jeffrey Harris "said the real danger is to suggest that government weigh the savings from early deaths in making public policy decisions."  He noted that Viscusi's study does not include "a key benefit to our society:  We value life."

<p>  -Jeanne Scott

<center><h3><a name=aa17>San Francisco Files its Own "Medicaid" Suit</a></h3></a></center>


San Francisco, CA May 16, 1996. The San Francisco Board of Supervisors Health, Public Safety and Environment committee today passed a resolution calling on the city to file a class-action lawsuit against the tobacco industry to seek payment of health care costs associated with smoking-related diseases.

<p>Supervisor Angela Alioto's resolution will be acted on by the full board within two weeks, according to AP, which also says SF Mayor Willie Brown "is expected to sign the measure." Alioto told AP that 23 other counties in California would join the suit.

<p>In the topsy-turvy world of California politics, the characters grow more interesting all the time:

<p>PETE WILSON

<p>Last year California Governor Pete Wilson signed the country's most sweeping statewide smoking restrictions. He also appointed as his presidential campaign chairman Craig Fuller, then senior vice president for corporate affairs at Philip Morris. For the last few years, Wilson has been in a fierce battle with tobacco control advocates as he has sought to gut the voter-approved Proposition 99 funds for tobacco education. Among Wilson's allies--the California Medical Association.

<p>KIMBERLY BELSHE

<p>In December of 1993, Wilson appointed Kimberly Belshe--the chief Southern California tobacco spokesperson against Proposition 99--to head the Department of Health Services, which runs the program. Yet in October of 1994, Belshe fought to save the disputed "I believe nicotine is not addictive" Prop. 99 ad, which had been called libelous by lawyers for then-RJR head James Johnston. Belshe strongly vilified the "strong-arm tactics" she said RJR lawyers were using to intimidate stations from running the ad.

<p>WILLIE BROWN

<p>When San Francisco, Mayor Willie Brown was State Assembly speaker, he was known as "the Marlboro Man," and in at least one year reportedly accepted more tobacco funds than any other politician in the country--including Virginia Rep. Thomas Bliley.

<center><h3><a name=aa18>LAWSUITS: Woman Can Sue Supermarket for Youth Sales--Appeals Court</a></h3></a></center></h3>

San Francisco, CA. June 29, 1996. A state appeals court today allowed a woman to sue a store chain for selling cigarettes to minors.

<p><i>[California's] unfair competition statute provides that enforcement actions may be brought by the state attorney general, any district attorney, any city attorney, a city prosecutor 'or by any person acting for the interests of itself, its members or the general public,</i> ruled the 1st District Court of Appeals, overturning a lower court's decision by a vote of 3-0.

<p>The "person acting for the interests of ... the general public" is Carol Levy, of Stop Youth Addiction, a one-woman corporation, according to UPI. Her son, Donald Driscoll is the attorney handling the suit. Levy's husband died of lung cancer in the 60s.

<p>SYA's suit was filed against Lucky Stores, Inc., a supermarket chain. The suit seeks $10 billion restitution of profits from illegal sales to minors, an injunction against further sales, and attorney's fees.

<p>"When you walk into Lucky's with a check, they're very careful [about checking ID] because they could lose money. When you walk in saying you're 18 they don't care.," said Driscoll.

<p>The suit arose out of a sting operation Levy organized in 1994. The 100 other stores caught in the sting agreed to settle by signing a contract promising not to sell cigarettes to minors, and in some cases by also paying as much as $100 a day for SYA's legal fees.

<p>Lucky refused.

<p>In response to the ruling, a Lucky lawyer said: "Lucky and several other stores do not believe it is appropriate for a private profit-making corporation to hire minors to violate the law so that he can sue to recover attorneys fees. . .  Lucky believes very strongly that the enforcement of California's penal code provisions properly rests with California prosecutors, particularly in this case where prosecutors are not permitted to bring a lawsuit . . . unless they comply with very strict procedures."

<p>Lucky claims it has strict procedures in place--including a cigarette cabinet which must be unlocked with each sale, and which each time reminds the clerk to check for ID. Lucky will appeal to California's Supreme Court.

<p>
<li>TALLAHASSEE, FL. May 29, 1996: Florida State Circuit Judge Harold Cohen set trial for August 4, 1997 for the state's $1.4 billion "Medicaid" suit, and lifted a stay on the taking of depositions.
<li>NEW ORLEANS, LA. May 23, 1996. CASTANO: A three-judge appeals panel today agreed with tobacco industry lawyers that a class action of 50 million smokers would be too unwieldy to move through the court, and voided a previous judge's certification. The panel ruled that the issues involved (addiction and the industry's knowledge of smoking's effects) are too new and too weighty to be decided all at once for every smoker in the country, and would be better worked out in state venues. The original plaintiffs may still proceed, and Castano lawyers had in fact prepared a "Plan B". Lawyers will begin immediately filing state-level suits. LIggett indicated it will still abide by the terms of its settlement.  Tobacco stocks soared on the news.

<p><li>NEW ORLEANS, LA. May 12, 1996. CASTANO: Plaintiffs in the class action suit filed a motion for preliminary approval of a proposed settlement reached with Liggett Tobacco on March 12, 1996. No date for a fairness hearing on the matter has been set.
<p><li>May 3, 1996. INDIANA CLASS ACTION: A class action suit was filed against tobacco companies on behalf of all Indiana residents who allege addiction to nicotine.

<p><li>TALLAHASSEE, FL. 5/10/96. Tobacco defendants' motions for rehearing were denied by the Court of Appeals for the Third District of Florida in two class action lawsuits. The defendants were seeking decertification of both classes:

<ul><li>BROIN V. PHILIP MORRIS COMPANIES, INC., involves non-smoking flight attendants who work or have worked for U.S. airlines and allege injuries from exposure to ETS.

<li>ENGLE V. R.J. REYNOLDS TOBACCO COMPANY involves plaintiffs who are Florida citizens and residents who claim they have become addicted to cigarette smoke and have suffered injuries as a result. </ul>

<p>Defendants intend to appeal both decisions to the Florida Supreme Court.

<p><li>5/1/96 MARYLAND MEDICAID SUIT: Maryland became the 8th state to file a "Medicaid" suit against the tobacco industry today, and the first to charge the industry deceptively and fraudulently targeted minorities through the use of inner-city billboards.. The suit will be handled by Baltimore Orioles part-owner PETER ANGELOS, who made his fortune representing workers in asbestos-related lawsuits. RJ Reynolds said cigarette taxes more than cover any smoking-related health-care costs.

<p><li>5/1/96 CONNECTICUT MEDICAID SUIT: Connecticut's attorney-general Richard Blumenthal said Connecticut plans to file a "Medicaid" suit against the tobacco industry, probably by early summer.
.
<li>5/12/96. <a name="aaashes">"ASHES TO ASHES," </a> received a glowing review in the NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW.

<center><h3><a name=aa19>ART: San Diego Museum Cancels PM Sponsorship</a></h3></center></a>

San Diego, CA. May 1, 1996 The San Diego Museum of Art has canceled Philip Morris' sponsorship of a summer exhibit of life-size sculptures of wild horses--a subject emblematic of PM's "Marlboro" brand--which would have run during the Philip Morris-sponsored Republican convention in San Diego (Aug. 12-15), and been the focus of receptions and events. The exhibition is now at risk, as no alternate sponsor has been found.

<p>The show's sculptor, Deborah Butterfield, had previously told the LA Times that her father had died at 63 of heart disease aggravated by his smoking, and that she was uncomfortable with the PM sponsorship, but the museum had told her no other sponsors were available. 

<p>"I really have to lay down with the devil to do this but . . . you know, you make choices," Butterfield told the Times. Now that the museum has reponded to the calls of protest it received, it is hoping the community will help.

<p>It is the second area event which has snubbed Philip Morris' sponsorship. Last month, Del Mar Fair Board canceled its arrangement to let PM sell Marlboros at the "Fiesta Latino Day."

<p>The art world has experienced an unprecedented distancing of artists from Philip Morris sponsorship recently. Protests were made at "1965-1975: Reconsidering the Object of Art," exhibits in New York and California last year.  Adrian Piper withdrew her work, saying she'd be glad to hang portraits of her parents who died of tobacco-related diseases instead. Long-time tobacco industry critic Hans Haacke hung a "disclaimer" next to his work. 10 other artists in the show also protested, including Sol LeWitt, Yvonne Rainer and Victor Burgin.
<p><strong>Sites to see:</strong>
<li>Visit the San Diego Museum of Art's <a href="http://www.sddt.com/~sdma/files/exhibits/exhibits5.html"> Butterfield Page</a>, which as of May 2, still read, "Deborah Butterfield is sponsored by Philip Morris Companies Inc." 

<li>Some of Haacke's works, from an exhibition canceled at the Guggenheim because they dealt with "'specific social situations' not considered art," are listed at: <a href="http://fileroom.aaup.uic.edu/FileRoom/documents/Cases/86hansHaacke.html"> The File Room</a> of censorship.

<center><h3><a name=aa20>Writer Slams Magazines on Tobacco Ads</a></h3></a></center>

Boston, MA. May 10, 1996. Today's Boston Globe carried an article titled "Sound of Silence on Tobacco Ads" by staff writer Derrick Z. Jackson, who searched recent popular magazines for articles on health, and found no mention of the number one preventable cause of death (smoking) in any that carried tobacco ads.

<p>Jackson cited the 1992  study published in the New England Journal of Medicine that found that magazines that did not accept cigarette ads were 40 percent more likely to have articles on the dangers of smoking.

<p>One example he cited: "The cover of the May 13 Fortune was devoted to men battling prostate cancer. But the call to fight lung cancer, which is as simple as refusing to pick up a cigarette, is close to nonexistent"

<p>Other magazines Jackson mentioned that had health articles, but nothing on tobacco were:

<li>Elle
<li>Family Circle
<li>First for Women
<li>Harper's Bazaar
<li>Ladies Home Journal
<li>Mademoiselle
<li>McCall's
<li>Mirabella
<li>New Woman
<li>Swing
<li>Women's World

<p>Besides buying silence on tobacco issues, Jackson said such ads buy legitimacy. With ads prominently displayed in other popular magazines like People, Time, Sports Illustrated, Life, Rolling Stone, Entertainment Weekly, Spin, Hot Rod, Motor Trend, Sport, New York and Premiere, Jackson said, "you can understand why . . . many teen-agers see smoking as legitimate."

<p><i>Magazines publishers who accept ads from tobacco,</i> Jackson concluded, <i>do not have the courage to say the profits are picked up over someone's dead body.</i>

<center><h3><a name=aa21>PEOPLE: Herb Caen Has Inoperable Lung Cancer</a></h3></a></center>


May 30, 1996. San Francisco's most beloved columnist, Herb Caen, told his readers today he has inoperable lung cancer.

<p>In explaining his column's uncharacteristically sporadic appearances in the San Francisco Chronicle, he said, "I do wish I could have told you that my long silences were indeed due to The World's Greatest Hangover." </p>

<p>After disclosing how his doctor found a "pigeon-egg" sized tumor on his right lung, Caen, 80,  said, "To answer your next question, no, I don't smoke but I did for about 40 years, with no blips on the X-rays. I quit cold turkey some 25 years ago, but the specialists simply shrug off this kind of information. And so, in a lightning flash, I passed from the land of the well to the world of the unwell, where I will now dwell for what I hope is a long time.''</p>

<p>"My life is now controlled by a dream team of specialists, who keep my once-pristine medicine cabinet stocked with pills -- the cabinet that once contained nothing more medical than Band-Aids. Old ones. Foolish pride: I considered myself indestructible," he wrote.</p>

<p>Caen said his chemotherapy would limit his future columns to three-a-week, at most.</p>

<p>"The Sackamenna  Kid" (Sacramento, where he was born in 1916) fell hopelessly in love with "The City" on a visit when a child, moved there in 1936, and has been writing a daily column of opinion, puns, and area gossip and arcana for almost 60 years, since 1938. He was diagnosed 5 weeks ago.</p>

<p>In just the last 2 months:</p>

<ul>
<li>He was awarded a special Pulitzer award for his "extraordinary and continuing contribution as a voice and conscience of his city."</li> 

<li>He married his long-time girl friend Ann Moller (his fourth marriage).</li> 

<li>The name of the Embarcadero Promenade was changed to "Herb Caen Way."</li> 

</ul>
<p>In 1986, Caen reported on "high-school age kids gleefully grabbing for free Yves St. Laurent perfumed ciggies being handed out on street corners" with no apparent requests for identification.</p>

<p>More recently, he supported his close friend Willie Brown for Mayor of SF, saying, "What you see is all the flash and dash, but what you get is a caring, hard-working, smart, honest, brilliant, wonderful man." Brown is known to others as the "Marlboro Man" for the extraordinary amount of money he received from tobacco interests when he was speaker of the California Assembly.</p>

<center><h3><a name=aa22>PEOPLE: Morton Downey, with Lung Cancer, to Fight Tobacco</a></h3></a></center>

New York, NY. June 18, 1996. Morton Downey, Jr., the outspoken, chain-smoking talk-show-host-turned-pro-tobacco-advocate has revealed he has lung cancer, and will begin an anti-smoking campaign aimed at kids.

<p>Downey, 63, a former 3-4-pach-a-day smoker, told Reuters, "Just because I've been foolish in not listening to medical warnings about the dangers of smoking, doesn't mean that I shouldn't deliver a strong anti-smoking message to today's youth in their own vernacular."

<p>Downey plans a TV special called, "Tough Guy," according to AP, at the end of which a kid is being pressured to smoke. With an appropriate gesture, the kid responds, "Smoke this!."

<p>Only last January, Downey was a board member of the National Smokers Alliance. He quit, he said, when he "realized that the major tobacco companies were lying when they said they weren't adding dangerous levels of nicotine to cigarette tobacco. They're nothing but tobacco terrorists."

<p>Reuters said Downey was due to "undergo surgery on his right lung" within weeks.

<p>Downey pioneered the modern era of "shock TV" with his syndicated "The Morton Downey, Jr. Show" in the late 1980s.

<center><h3><a name=aa23><i>Exeunt Omnes:</i> RJR's Johnston is Last of the Tobacco 7 to Exit Business</a></h3></a></center>

<i>I'm considering Friday the first day of my new, more balanced life. Over those seven years . . . I pushed off the people and things that I love in order to meet the constant demands of the job. I finally decided it was time to put my life back in balance.</i>

<p>Winston-Salem, NC. June 28, 1996 James R. Johnston, vice- chairman and director of RJR Nabisco Holdings and CEO of RJ Reynolds Tobacco Worldwide, retired today.

<p>Johnston is the last of the 7 tobacco executives who testified before Congress in April, 1994 to resign from the business. Analysts say the departure of so many top executives in any industry in so short a time--2 years and 2 months--is extremely unusual.

<p>Johnston had worked for RJR in the early eighties, but was at CitiBank when asked in 1989 to head the domestic tobacco arm of debt-laden RJR, which had just been the subject of a $29 Billion LBO, and had seen the humiliating failure of its "smokeless" cigarette, <i>Premier.</i> Under his tenure, morale improved, but RJR's tobacco business remained stagnant, firmly in second place behind titan Philip Morris.

<p>What market gains the company made came primarily from the success of its expensively promoted Camel brand--which led in turn to a continuing barrage of criticism of the campaign, which was accused of targeting youth. Johnston gained national attention at the 1994 Waxman hearings, and was the only executive to talk with Ted Koppel on Nightline.

<p>Johnston indicated that after 7 years tending to a business in perpetual crisis, he wanted to spend more time with his wife Beverly and two daughters. Johnston's only son, Michael, 18, shot and killed himself in his bedroom in February, 1995.

<p>Andrew J. Schindler, head of U.S. operations, and Pierre de Labouchere, head of the international unit will now report directly to RJR Nabisco chairman and CEO Steven Goldstone--who only last May succeeded Charles M. Harper.

<h4><a name=aa24>SIDEBAR: THE HISTORIC 1994 CONGRESSIONAL APPEARANCE</a></h4>
The tobacco company executives who appeared before Henry Waxman's (D-CA) House Subcommittee on Health and the Environment beginning April 14, 1994, were (from left to right in the famous photo):

<p><li>Donald S. Johnston, president and CEO of American Tobacco Company 
<br>Johnston retired December 22, 1994 when ATC was acquired by Brown & Williamson Tobacco. Johnston had been with ATC since January 6, 1986; he had previously worked for Brown & Williamson Tobacco from October 23, 1965 until January, 1985. Johnston said ATC "has no desire or intent to manipulate nicotine."
<ul>QUOTE: [N]othing is done in the tobacco processing or manufacture of cigarettes or filters by the American Tobacco Co. to increase nicotine beyond that naturally occurring in tobacco . . . American has no desire or intent to 'manipulate' nicotine.</ul>

<p><li>Thomas Sandefur Jr., chairman and CEO of Brown and William Tobacco Corporation
<br> Sandefur left B&W at age 55 in June, 1995; the company cited medical reasons; Sandefur was reported to have a rare blood disease.

<p><li>Edward A. Horrigan, chairman and CEO of Liggett Group Inc. 
<br>Horrigan gave up his CEO position in June, 1994, and his chairmanship on Dec. 31, 1994. He had only been with Liggett for about a year when he testified; he was a major RJR management figure in the leveraged buyout of the company in 1989.
<ul>QUOTE: It is outrageous for you to assume that we (tobacco industry heads) meet and talk about this issue. . .  They are competitors, not conspirators.</ul>

<p><li>Andrew H. Tisch, chairman and CEO Lorillard Tobacco Company
<br>Tisch left both positions May 31, 1995 to take an expanded role at Lorillard's parent company, Loews Corp., which the Tisch family runs.
<ul>QUOTE: Lorillard does not take any steps to assure a minimal level of nicotine in our products.</ul>

<p><li>Joseph Taddeo, president of United States Tobacco Company
<br>Taddeo's resignation, said to be due to disappointing sales and disagreements with management at parent UST Inc., was announced in June, 1995.
<ul>QUOTES:
<li>U.S. Tobacco believes that no ingredient which it adds to tobacco in the manufacture of its smokeless tobacco products would result in adverse health consequences to a consumer of our product 
<li>Oral tobacco has not been established as a cause of mouth cancer
<li>Without revealing proprietary information, I can tell you that every ingredient which U.S. Tobacco adds to tobacco in the manufacture of its products is a common food item or approved for use in food, with the single exception of (an approved ingredient) for use in the manufacture of tobacco products
<li>Oral tobacco has not been established as a cause of mouth cancer</ul>

<p><li>James W. Johnston, CEO of R.J. Reynolds.
<br>Johston retired June 28, 1996.
<ul>QUOTES:
<li>If I thought that ad (the Joe Camel campaign) caused any young people to begin smoking, I'd pull it in a heartbeat
<li>Would you rather board a plane with a pilot who just smoked a cigarette or one with a pilot who just had a couple of beers or snorted cocaine or shot heroin or popped some pills?
<li>We do not do anything to hook smokers or keep them hooked. . . We no more manipulate nicotine in cigarettes than coffee makers manipulate caffeine. . . but no one is suggesting the FDA regulate coffee, cola or tea as drugs.
<li>Don't you think there are 45 million Americans who resent being characterized as helpless, pathetic addicts? You can characterize smokers as addicts, like some of these gentlemen did today, but common sense tells you they are not. My God, I'm no addict. I smoke. I've just been through a long day. You didn't see me biting a hole in this table, did you?
<li>If cigarettes are too dangerous to be sold, then ban them. Some smokers will obey the law, but many will not. People will be selling cigarettes out of the trunks of cars, cigarettes made by who knows who, made of who knows what.
<li>The goal of the anti-smoking industry is to bring back prohibition.
<li>WAXMAN: "Does smoking cause heart disease?
<br>JOHNSTON: It may
<br>WAXMAN: Does it cause lung cancer?
<br>JOHNSTON: It may
<br>WAXMAN: Emphysema?
<br>JOHNSTON: It may.</ul>

<p><li>William I. Campbell, CEO, Philip Morris USA
<br>Campbell retired in June, 1995 at 51; in September, 1995, he was hired to teach business courses at the University of Richmond; in January, 1996, he was hired to run Citicorp's branch banking operations worldwide as executive vice president for retail banking operations.
<ul>QUOTES: 
<li>Philip Morris does not manipulate nor independently control the level of nicotine in our products. . . . Cigarettes contain nicotine because it occurs naturally in tobacco. Nicotine contributes to the taste of cigarettes and the pleasures of smoking. . . When creating a cigarette for a tar category, we select a particular tobacco blend and flavors to provide 'uniqueness' to the product. So how do we manipulate or independently control nicotine as our critics charge? The answer is we don't. We accept the nicotine levels that result from this process.
<li>Smokers are not drug users or addicts, and we do not appreciate being characterized as such.</ul>

<p><strong>THE FOLLOWING IS THE FAMOUS "ADDICTION" EXCHANGE:</strong>

<p>REP. WYDEN: Let me ask you first, and I'd like to just go down the row, whether each of you believes that nicotine is not addictive. I've heard virtually all of you touch on it--yes or no, do you believe nicotine is not addictive?
<br>WILLIAM I. CAMPBELL (Philip Morris): I believe that nicotine is not addictive, yes.
<br>REP. WYDEN: Mr. Johnson...
<br>JAMES JOHNSTON (RJ Reynolds): Uh, Congressman, cigarettes and nicotine clearly do not meet the classic definition of addiction. There is no intoxication--
<br>REP. WYDEN: We'll take that as a no. And again, time is short, if you can just, I think each of you believe nicotine is not addictive, I'd just like to have this for the record.
<br>JOSEPH TADDEO (US Tobacco): I don't believe that nicotine or our products are addictive.
<br>ANDREW TISCH (P Lorillard): I believe that nicotine is not addictive.
<br>EDWARD HORRIGAN (Liggett Group): I believe that nicotine is not addictive.
<br>THOMAS SANDEFUR (Brown & Williamson): I believe that nicotine is not addictive.
<br>DONALD JOHNSTON (American Tobacco Co.): And I too believe that nicotine is not addictive.

<center><h3><a name=aa25>OBIT: American Brands Director Alley, 66, Commits Suicide</a></h3></a></center></h3>

New Canaan, CT. July 26, 1996. William J. Alley, who was chairman and CEO of American Brands in 1994 when the diversified company announced its intention to sell its American Tobacco unit to Brown & Williamson, committed suicide in his home today, according to police.

<p>Alley came into tobacco from the life insurance business. He was chairman of Franklin Life when the company was acquired by American Brands in 1979, and was named CEO of American Brands in May, 1987. He was still CEO in April, 1994, when Donald Johnston, president of American's tobacco unit, told Henry Waxman's Congressional subcommittee, "And I too believe that nicotine is not addictive."

<p>At the time of his death, Alley was a director of American Brands. He was also serving as a director of Olin Corp., Amsted Industries Inc., Central Illinois Public Service Co., Cipsco Inc. and Rayonier Inc..

<p>He is survived by his wife, Deborah, and 5 children.

<p>Two other prominent tobacco figures died this month: Thomas Sanderfur (July 15, 1996), the Brown & Williamson CEO who testified in 1994, and former Brown & Williamson General Counsel Addison Yeaman (88, July 7, 1996), who wrote, "we are, then, in the business of selling nicotine, an addictive drug effective in the release of stress mechanisms."

<h3><a name=aa26>NEW WEB SITES</a></h3>


<h3><a name=aa27>THE FUNNY PAGES</a></h3>


CBS-TV's "48 Hours," April 10, 1996, featured a segment on Dennis Parone's "Cannabis Buyer's Club" in San Francisco. One shot focused on a handwritten sign hanging above the sales counter: 

<p>
<strong><blockquote>Thank you for POT smoking.
<br>PLEASE do NOT smoke tobacco here.</blockquote></strong>

The US Tobacco Company has announced that between now and Dec. 31 it will donate a portion of its sales--at least $1M--to the National Volunteer Fire Council. In return US Tobacco asked that for the rest of the year, everyone pretend that cigarettes don't cause cancer.
<br>--Norm MacDonald, Saturday Night Live, May 11, 1996

<p>A secret R.J. Reynolds marketing report in 1984 stressed the importance of selling cigarettes to young people to "replace" other smokers. Says the Cutler Daily Scoop, "Fortunately, plans for a 'Nicotine at Nite' cable channel fell through." 
<br>--Los Angeles Times, July 12, 1996

<p>Jay Leno offered this plot for Independence Day II: ``Bob Dole is president. He convinces the aliens that smoking is safe. They all get emphysema and die."

