<p><center>HEALTH</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>

<p><center>FEDERAL</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
1/6/96. The FTC is looking at new ways to list tar and nicotine contents on cigarette ads. The new ways might reflect the range of nicotine levels actually inhaled, which are dependent on an individual's smoking patterns. The FTC has no authority to regulate listings on cigarette packs themselves.</p>
<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>


<p><center>LOCAL</p>

<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, IL. 1/2/95. Possession of tobacco products by minors has been banned by the Board of Trustees. Fines range from $5 to $75. The ban goes into effect immediately.</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
<p>WINSTON-SALEM, NC. 1/6/96: The city's leading employer is no longer RJR Nabisco, but a hospital/medical center (Baptist Hospital and Bowman Gray School of Medicine). Bowman Gray was a noted former CEO of RJ Reynolds Tobacco Co.</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
ROANOKE, VA 1/6/96: The Tobacco Communities Project is attempting to bring together all factions involved in the tobacco controversy together for "town meetings" to promote understanding. There have been 4 so far. The meetings of growers, manufacturers, wholesalers, bankers, legislators and health care professionals was the brainchild of Rebecca Reeve of the Institute for Quality Health at the University of Virginia.</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
SANTA MONICA, CA 1/6/96: Under pressure from businesses, Santa Monica relaxed its tough 1994 smoking ban; allows smoking in bars, meeting rooms</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
LA, CA 1/6/96: Smoking is now banned in bars at LAX. Smoking now allowed only in a single designated area in Tom Bradley International Terminal lounge.</p>
<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a></center>
<p>INTERNATIONAL</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
CANADA, 3/14/96: Vancouver, BC has passed a 100% smokefree ban at restaurants that allow children.
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
INDIA 1/6/96: Tobacco giant ITC has been ordered to pay 7.99 billion rupees ($235 million) in excise taxes owed from 1983-1987, when, the government alleged, ITC took part in a conspiracy with retailers to charge higher prices than those marked on the packages. ITC, whose stock dipped on the ruling, will file a challenge. ITC may ask 31% shareholder BAT Industries or other financial institutions for financing to pay the charge.</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
HONG KONG 1/6/96: A proposed rule to ban almost all tobacco advertising--including  'alibi marketing' or 'trademark diversification' (attaching the brand name or logo to a non-tobacco product)--is being fought furiously by the tobacco industry. The industry is using the free speech arguments successfully employed by Canadian cigarette companies to rescind an advertising ban. In fact, the lawyer who argued the case has been brought to Hong Kong.</p>
<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
CHINA 1/8/96: Yunnan Province has become the largest tobacco producing province in the largest tobacco producing country in the world. 1/3 of the southeastern province's tobacco output was in the form of leaf tobacco, and 1/6 in the form of manufactured cigarettes, according to Xinhua news agency.
<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a></center>
CHINA 4/1/96 The Medical Sciences University in Shanghai today became China's first smoke-free University. 2,000 faculty, staff and students--including the University's president--signed a 20-meter lenght of cloth to celebrate the event. A group set up last year to ban smoking on the campus said smokers would not be sought for enrollment, and that some University-affiliated hospitals refuse to hire smokers.
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a></center>
SOUTH AFRICA: 4/1/96 Monday's <i>Business Day</i> reports that the government is considering a tobacco advertising ban.
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a></center>


<p>BUSINESS</p>
<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center><br>
<p>LAWSUITS</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
1/3/96: LAWSUITS: Flight Attendants' Class Action Status Certified
<P>In the airline workers' second-hand smoke case, flight attendants' class-action certification was upheld by the District Court of Appeals in Florida for the third district. The ruling was expected. Two of the three judges had sat on the original decision to grant certification. Philip Morris said it will ask the panel to rehear the case. If the same decision prevails, the tobacco companies will likely appeal the decision to an 11-judge appellate court.</p>
<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
<p>SOCIETY</p>
<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>


<p>PEOPLE</p>

<p><center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
<p>SPORTS</p>
<p>DARTS: Dec. 29, 1995. 30-year-old Dutchman Roland Scholten won the British Open Darts in London today, winning $3,000. <i>I was not too confident because I have not been feeling well for a couple of days, </i> he said. <i> I'm a heavy smoker but I didn't touch a cigarette all day and didn't have a drink until it was all over.</i>

<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
<p>THE FUNNY PAGES</p>
<center><IMG border=0 SRC="alumshort2.gif"></a>
</center>
From News Of The Weird By Chuck Shepherd</p>

<p>Laina Baumann, 17, was crowned the 60th queen of the Charles County Fair in LaPlata, Md., in September. Because the county has historically been a leading tobacco producer, the pageant winner has long been referred to as Queen Nicotina. </p>

