<!--End of Sequential Linkers-->

Reprinted with permission from <a href="mailto:news@mealeys.com">Mealy Publications</a> (1-800-MEALEYS) in Wayne, Pa.


	<hr>

<h3><center>Historic Tobacco Settlement Close To Completion
</center></h3>

JACKSON, Miss. " The historic first settlement of a tobacco lawsuit could be wrapped up in a few days or a few weeks with Liggett Group Inc., sources familiar with the negotiations speculate.

<p>A source, who did not want to be identified, told Mealey Publications that negotiations on the proposed settlement are continuing and that the bulk of the deal has been finalized. However, the source could not comment on what issues are still in dispute.</p>

<p>If successful, the proposed agreement " which Mississippi Attorney General Mike Moore's office says could reach $2 billion " would be the first settlement of a cigarette lawsuit. Negotiations have been going on for a month between Liggett, Brooke Group Ltd., attorneys and several attorneys general, including Moore.</p>

<p>Under the terms of the agreement, Liggett would, among other things, withdraw its objection to the Food and Drug Administration's jurisdiction over tobacco and agree to implement some of the agency's regulations. The tobacco company would also agree to compensate Mississippi, Florida, Massachusetts and West Virginia for past and current expenses incurred in providing medical care to residents allegedly suffering from smoking-related illnesses.</p>

<p>Minnesota, which also has a Medicaid reimbursement suit against the tobacco industry, is still considering participation in the deal.</p>

<p>The proposed deal could include RJR Nabisco if its shareholders elect a Brooke Group representative to the company's board of directors. The new board would spin off the company's food business and submit to shareholders a proposal to merge with Liggett. If the shareholders approve the merger, RJR would be bound by the agreement.</p>

<p>To cover future tobacco-related state health care costs, Liggett (and possibly RJR) would additionally pay the four settling states 2.5 percent of their pre-tax profits or $25 million annually, whichever is greater, over the 25-year life of the proposed settlement.</p>

<p>Furthermore, the settling defendants would agree to establish a fund for other states that have not filed lawsuits against the tobacco industry but may choose to do so in the future. Depending on the number of states that would join the proposed settlement, Liggett (and perhaps RJR) would pay $50 million annually or 5 percent of their pre-tax profits into this fund.</p>

<p>The Wall Street Journal reported that the deal would also dismiss Liggett from the massive Castano class action in New Orleans. The Journal added that the agreement would bar class members, which is essentially all current smokers in the United States, from suing the company for their alleged nicotine addiction.</p>

<p>A source told Mealey Publications that court approval would be necessary in the Castano class action but would most likely not be necessary in the four state Medicaid cases. Appeals of the Castano certification order are pending before the Fifth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals.</p>

<p>However, the Wall Street Journal reported that there is an "escape clause" that allows Liggett to get out of the deal " if other tobacco companies win in the same suits Liggett proposes to settle; if not enough Castano class members decide to participate in the deal; and if additional states file Medicaid reimbursement suits and refuse to participate in the settlement.</p>

<p>Further details will be covered in subsequent issues of The Report.</p>

<HR><address>
