<p></a>
<a href=http://csc-6203s.mgh.harvard.edu/QuitNet/QuitNews/smokgun/sg_today.html><li>Mass. Tobacco Control Program </a> is still alive, but its funding has continually been cut, subverting the purpose of the voters' approval of Question 1 funds for tobacco education. Plus, Gov. Weld is conspicously silent about the Mass. Attorney General's lawsuit against the tobacco companies. Under pressure from opinion polls and blistering attacks from once-staunch political allies, Weld recently (Dec. 7, 1995) retreated from his plan to take $60 million from the $77 million approved by the voters on Question 1. However, $13 million used for a hard-hitting media campaign will be added to present school tobacco control programs under Weld's current proposed budget. Mass. residents still need to let their legislators know where they stand. For background, read the <a href=http://www.library.ucsf.edu/tobacco/q1/> UCSF study.</a></li>

