<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Smoke Alarm Nov. 21, 1996 HBO &amp; Consumers Reports</TITLE>
<META NAME="resource type" content="document">
<META NAME="description" content="The Tobacco BBS WebPage provides a free resource center focusing on tobacco issues and featuring tobacco-related news, addresses, history, book lists, and quit-smoking tips.">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Gene Borio">
<META NAME="keywords" content="tobacco cigarettes smoking health politics history history cigar cigars">
<META NAME="rating" CONTENT="General">
<META NAME="revisit-after" CONTENT="31 days">
<META NAME="VW96.objecttype" CONTENT="Homepage">
<META NAME="ROBOTS" CONTENT="INDEX,FOLLOW">
<META NAME="keywords" content="tobacco cigarettes smoking health politics nicotine withdrawal cigar cigars drugs smokers smoker smoke history news tobacco addresses tobacco control books clove cigarettes smoking in society">
<META NAME="distribution" content=global>
<META NAME="copyright" content="Copyight 1996 Gene Borio, Tobacco BBS (212-982-4645; WebPage: http://www.tobacco.org) Original material may be reprinted in any non-commercial venue as long as it is accompanied by this notice.">
<META NAME="Reply-to" content=geneb@tobacco.org>

</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>HBO and Consumer Reports Television Look at The
Hazards of Smoking and Show How Kids are Targeted by The Tobacco
Industry</H2>

<P>Anyone who has not tried smoking by age 19 most likely will not
start. As a result, tobacco companies must do everything in their
power to attract young people if they are to replace the 5,000
smokers who either die or quit every day in America. </P>

<P>This November, HBO and Consumer Reports Television, the team
responsible for the acclaimed ``Buy Me That!'' shows, join forces
once again for the timely family special SMOKE ALARM: THE UNFILTERED
TRUTH ABOUT CIGARETTES. A revealing look at the tobacco industry's
marketing efforts to children, the teenage smoking epidemic, and the
hazards of tobacco, this exclusive presentation debuts THURSDAY, NOV.
21 (7:00-7:30 p.m. ET), the day of ``The Great American Smokeout.''
</P>

<P>Other playdates: Nov. 24 and 26, and Dec. 2 and 6.) </P>

<P>Using a variety of entertaining approaches, this fast-paced
special combines live-action segments, animated shorts and comments
from actual kids to underscore the dangers of tobacco smoking and
chewing. The show emphasizes the harsh realities of tobacco's health
hazards, including facts about cancer and premature death. For
example, the risk of lung cancer at age 50 is 350% higher for a
person who started smoking at age 13, compared to a person who
started at age 23. </P>

<P>``Kids do not like to be made fools of,'' said Sheila Nevins,
senior vice president of documentary and family programinng at HBO,
and an executive producer of the program. ``Our aim is to show them
how they're being misled and negatively influenced by cigarette
advertising and promotions.''</P>

<P>Segments of SMOKE ALARM: THE UNFILTERED TRUTH ABOUT CIGARETTES
include:</P>

<P>``The Lounge Lungs,'' a couple of lung-puppets who provide segues
between sections of the show with bad puns about smoking. Featuring
the voices of Joseph Bologna and Renee Taylor, the red-and-brown
Lounge Lungs, afflicted with emphysema, are a striking illustration
of tobacco's health consequences. The two were created specially for
the show by veteran puppeteer Marty Robinson (''The Little Shop of
Horrors,'' ``Sesame Street''), and operated by Robinson and Pam
Arciero (''Sesame Street''). </P>

<P>``Butts,'' a high-energy mock game show that serves up the facts
about smoking to its contestants (actors Jeffrey Landman and Diane
Lozada). The smarmy host (played by Peter Jacobson) dumps contestants
who give wrong answers into a large ashtray and locks them into a
container filled with second-hand smoke. </P>

<P>An inside look at the fictional ``American Pride Tobacco Company''
and its strategy sessions for a new youth cigarette called ``Frank
Mule.'' Top executives (played by Paul Hecht and Veanne Cox) talk
about how to increase cigarette sales by enticing young people to
smoke with promotions, advertising and merchandise. In fact, the
Federal Trade Commission reports (1995) that the tobacco industry
spends more than $6 billion on marketing, advertising and promotion,
up from $2 billion in 1993. </P>

<P>A kid (actor Josh Soboslai) with multiple cigarette premiums,
nicknamed ``The Marlboro Man,'' who professes the joys of smoking
because of the ``great stuff'' he gets from companies for smoking a
quantity of cigarettes. Items he has ordered from Marlboro catalogs
include CD players, t-shirts, lanterns and baseball caps. Consumer
Reports has found that one in four kids who smoke own a premium item,
suggesting they are particularly responsive to premiums, promotions
and logos.</P>

<P>A 1991 study by the University of Georgia found that 30% of
3-year-olds and 91% of 6-year-olds could match the Joe Camel cartoon
character with the cigarette, and another 1991 study, by the
University of Massachusetts, found that nearly 98% of high-school
students recognized the character, compared with only 72% of adults.
</P>

<P>``Cigarette Breakout,'' a stop-motion puppet segment in which
packs of talking cigarettes plot to escape from the shelves of a
store. Tony Danza, Lou Diamond Phillips and Tone Loc provide voices.
</P>

<P>In interview segments, teenagers confess their addiction to
tobacco, with some admitting to starting as early as age 9. Federal
Drug Administration research indicates that the average age for
starting smoking is 14.5 years old. Consumer Reports has found that
more than three million children and adolescents smoke cigarettes,
and their main reasons for smoking are that they are easy to buy,
their friends smoke, they can't stop, and ``it's cool.'' In fact, 80%
of smoking teens say that at least one best friend smokes. Seven out
of ten high-school seniors who smoke say that they wish they'd never
started.</P>

<P>Other telling quotes from kids in the show: </P>

<UL>
   <LI>``I am not addicted; I can quit anytime I want.'' 
   
   <LI>``I've never been carded to buy smokes.'' 
   
   <LI>``I get high off cigarettes.''
   
   <LI>``I think I definitely have the right to smoke.'' 
   
   <LI>``I've tried to quit six times in the last five months. It's a
   matter of headaches, shaking, and coming outside and seeing all
   your friends smoking.''
   
   <LI>``I get winded really quickly.''
   
   <LI>``We're all gonna die sometime, might as wel have fun.'' 
</UL>

<P>The 17-year partnership between Consumer Reports and HBO has
yielded more than 30 specials. Among them are programs geared toward
children, including the award-winning ``Buy Me That! A Kid's Survival
Guide to TV Advertising'' series, which showed kids how to
discriminate fact from fiction in commercials, focusing on product
instructions, gimmicks, celebrity endorsements, and product
performance for toys, food and games. The 1990 special ``Earth to
Kids: A Guide to Products for a Healthy Planet'' demonstrated to
young people why conservation is important and how recycling can be
fun, using everyday items such as toothpaste pumps and juice boxes.
In the '80s, HBO aired the series ``Consumer Reports Presents,''
which featured advisory programs like ``The Food Show,'' ``The
Medicine Show,'' ``The All-Around-the-House Show,'' ``The Smart Buy
Show,'' ``The Dollar and Sense Show'' and ``The Car Show.''</P>

<P>``We've benefited from audiences' hunger for consumer information;
they need a relible, unbiased source to turn to in today's confusing
and sometimes misleading marketplace,'' said Joyce Newman, the
director of Consumer Reports Television and an executive producer for
all the programs. Also produced by the 60-year-old publication is a
nationally syndicated news service that is seen on more 80 stations
in the U.S. and Canada. Because Consumer Reports accepts no
advertising and tests products independently of manufacturers, their
reputation precedes them. ``Consumer Reports is America's most
trusted source of information because we are independent,'' Newman
added. </P>

<P>SMOKE ALARM: THE UNFILTERED TRUTH ABOUT CIGARETTES is produced by
John Hoffman; written by Jeff Kindley; directed by Steve Oakes. For
Curious Pictures: senior producer, Russell A. Dube; executive
producers, Richard Winkler and David Starr. For Consumer Reports
Television: executive producer, Joyce H. Newman. For HBO: senior
producer, Carole Rosen; executive producer, Sheila Nevins. </P>

<P>Contact:</P>

<P>New York:</P>

<P>Tobe Becker or Katherine Pongracz (212) 512-5492 or 5658 </P>

<P>Los Angeles:</P>

<P>Nancy Lesser or Tonya Owens (310) 201-9274 or 9355 </P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

