s Guide</a> for getting the story. There's actually little about tobacco on this site(!), but there is <a href="http://www.crp.org/story/watch1.html"> Counterpunch's in-depth article on the "Contibutions Watch" fiasco.</a><li>12/30/96<a href="http://www.stlnet.com:8080/news/wires.nsf"> POSTNet's Hot Wires Search Page</a> Up-to-the-second news, searchable. From the St. Louis Post. Warning: they disappear within days. From the St. Louis Post<li>12/18/96<a href="http://www.hound.com/"> Newshound</a> Get AP, Mercury tobacco stories delivered to your mailbox.<li><A HREF="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/news/tob">Advocacy Institute</A> [gopher news service only]<p><li>10/20/96 <a href="http://www.mediafinder.com/"> MediaFinder</a> Find print journals, newsletters, mags, directories, etc.--from the <a href="http://www.mediafinder.com/detail.cfm?tid=0198530997&pubtitle=&pubtype=&pubcat=&audience=&freq=&ads=&lists=&kword=tobacco&maxhits=50&sr=1&er=10&showad=No&showlr=No "> Ashtray Journal</a> (for you collectors) to <a href="http://www.mediafinder.com/detail.cfm?tid=0198534648&pubtitle=&pubtype=&pubcat=&audience=&freq=&ads=&lists=&kword=tobacco&maxhits=50&sr=41&er=50&showad=No&showlr=No ">Tobacco Life</a> Also, see media lists.</i><li>10/25/96 <a href="http://www.reuters.com/reutersnews/index.html"> Reuters Online Newsroom</a><li>10/18/96 For news junkies only--<strong>New Jersey Online's</strong> beta test of <a href="http://wire.ap.org/APwire/?SITE=NJO&SLOC=NJO&SKEY=ANYRAMAUNTHICOLDNE&SLOG=Default"> AP wire </a> (11/27/96--AP is revamping their terms of service; most previous suppliers of AP feeds are no longer functional.)<li>10/25/96 <a href="http://www.eurekalert.org/E-lert/current/mainpage.shtml"> EurekAlert</a>  Theoretically, "one-stop shopping" for the latest research findings in science, medicine and technology. Plus, resources for scientists, science writers and members of the public. Strangely, astonishingly, <i>nothing</i> about the recent p53 discovery. From American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS) <li>11/13/96<a href="http://www.yearbooknews.com/"> Broadcast Interview Source</a> Experts for journalists/broadcasters. You can do a search on tobacco, but they're not too complete, and not too fussy. (Maybe they had better luck verifying www.rbb.com). <a href="http://www.cjr.columbia.edu/tobacco/gd1.html"> Columbia Journalism Review</a> is a FAR more complete source of contacts.<p><li>01/22/97<a href="http://www.healthwatch.org"> Canadian News</a> with an attitude(!) can be seen at Terry Polevoy's site<p><li><a href="http://users.aol.com/srampton/center.html">PR Watch</a> Their new issue, due next week, focuses on tobacco and the State Affairs/"Contributions Watch/Philip Morris broo-ha-ha.<li><a href="http://www.nisc.com/reviews/tha_.htm">Tobacco & Health Abstracts</a> Must reading for the professional. THA "covers clinical research, trials, and studies drawn from over 1,500 publications, including legal, behavioral, biomedical and chemical journals, technical reports, books, conference proceedings, and theses."<li>10/21/96 The (Madison, WI) Isthmus is openly talking about an issue facing a lot of weeklies lately--a <a href="http://www.thedailypage.com/netforum/forum/a.cgi/3-17"> Fight over Tobacco Ads</a><li><a href="http://www.rbb.com/tobaclaw/">Tobacco Litigation Information</a> OK, this is a little tricky. The site <i>says</i> it has been set up by "the tobacco industry" (no further information provided) to be "a resource for journalists covering tobacco litigation issues." The site includes "legal documents, news articles, government reports and case briefs for free" (though you have to call an 800 number. Copyright considerations are very unclear here).<br><i>11/4/96: I've recently been re-alerted to the site by someone else, who claims to work for the PR firm that put up the site. Once again, questions about copyright and exact relationship to "the tobacco industry" went unanswered.I'm tired of it. Ask <a href="mailto:jklein@magicbox.com"> Jonathan Klein</a> or <a href="mailto:RBBPR@aol.com"> Tom Plummer</a> </i> <LI><A HREF="http://cancer.med.upenn.edu/cancer_news/">Cancer News <ul><LI><A href="http://oncolink.upenn.edu/cancer_news/nov5_1.html">The Great American Smokeout, November 17, 1995</a> </ul><li><a href="http://www.tobacco.neu.edu/"><strong> The Tobacco Control Resource Center (TCRC) and Tobacco Products Liability Project (TPLP)</strong> </a> A major web event! The spectacular newsletter-turned-ezine <i><a href="http://www.tobacco.neu.edu/tot/july96/July96.htm "> Tobacco on Trial</a></i> is produced by these folks from the Northeastern University School of Law. Don't miss it!<li><a href="http://andrewspub.com/tobacco">Tobacco Litigation Page</a></strong> from Andrews Publications' <i>Tobacco Industry Litigation Reporter.</i> This is <i><b> it</i></b> for legal data.<li><A HREF="http://akebono.stanford.edu/yahoo/Health/">Health Resources from Yahoo</A></li><li><a href="http://www.bottary.com "> Grady Carter Trial Site!</a> Many source materials directly from the trial--"a case overview, the actual verdict, legal team biographies, a look at what the tobacco companies knew, what they were telling the public, what the medical research showed, a chronology pertaining to warning labels, and a special section on what the labels should be telling us about the hazards of cigarette smoking."<li>11/30/96<a href="http://www.lawforum.net/els.htm"> Early, Ludwick & Sweeney L.L.C.</a> Tobacco litigation law firm<li><a href="http://www.essential.org/monitor/monitor_resources.html#keysearch"> The Multinational Monitor</a> tracks corporate activity, especially in the Third World, focusing on the export of hazardous substances, worker health and safety, labor union issues and the environment.<hr><a name = Newsarticles> <h3><a name=aa12>News Articles</a></h3></a><li>PBS has put their "The People and the Power Game" online, including the tobacco segment, <a href="http://www.pbs.org/powergame/files/unelected.html"> The Unelected</a>--plus a <a href="http://www.pbs.org/powergame/files/uneltrans.html">full transcript</a></a><p><li><a href="http://whyfiles.news.wisc.edu/">The Why Files--The Latest on Nicotine Addiction</a> From the National Science Foundation. Intense, thorough.<p><li><a href="http://www.oneworld.org/panos/panos_tobacco.html">Tobacco: The Smoke Blows South</a> Great 1994 article on tobacco expansion into developing countries around the world. Emphasis on agriculture & economics. Includes many international tobacco control addresses.<p><li><a href="http://www.nejm.org/publicM/1996/0335/0013/TOC/1.htm">Sept. 26, 1996 New England Journal of Medicine</a> has a <a href="http://www.nejm.org/publicM/1996/0335/0013/0988/1.htm"> Special Report on FDA Regulation</a> plus Reviews of <a href="http://www.nejm.org/publicM/1996/0335/0013/0981a/1.htm"><i>Ashes to Ashes</i></a> and <i> <a href="http://www.nejm.org/publicM/1996/0335/0013/0981b/1.htm">The Cigarette Papers</i></a><p><li><a href="http://www.essential.org/monitor/hyper/mm0192.html">Tobacco Imperialism</a> (1992), about the US Trade Rep's attack on Taiwanese tobacco control legislation. From the Multinational Monitor.<li><a href="http://www.cnnfn.com/news/9605/15/tobacco_attack_pkg/index.htm"> CNN's 3-Part "Tobacco Under Attack"</a><li><a href="http://www.farmjournal.com/CGI-SHL/DBML.EXE?TEMPLATE=/farmjournal/DISPLAY_ARTICLE.DBM&ID=605">Farm Journal: Surviving Without Tobacco</a><li><a href=http://ksgwww.harvard.edu/ksgpress/hilts.htm>The Tobacco Wars</a> New York Times reporter Phil Hilts addresses issues involved in covering tobacco stories. A discussion at the Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy at Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School of Government on November 14, 1995.</i><li><a href="http://desert.net/tw/11-22-95/cover.htm">"SMOKIN': How The American Tobacco Industry Employs PR Scum To