<h2>AIRLINE NEWS</h2>

<li> On July 1, 1996
<ul><li><strong>Air Mauritius</strong> banned smoking on all its flights.
<li><strong>Qantas</strong> banned smoking on all its flights.
<li><strong>Ansett Airlines</strong> (Australia) banned smoking on all its flights.</ul>
<li>On June 1, 1996

<ul><li> <strong>USAir</strong> banned smoking on all its flights

<li><strong>American Airlines</strong> banned smoking on flights to and from Europe, the Caribbean and to some destinations in Mexico

<li><strong>United Airlines</strong> banned smoking on flights across the Atlantic and within Europe (except between Washington Dulles International Airport and Milan, Italy). United also banned smoking on trans-Pacific flights and those within Asia except certain flights to Tokyo.</ul>

<h3>Airlines Flying 100% Smokefree:</h3>

<strong><i>(All flights between Canada, Australia and the US are 100% smokefree by treaty.)</strong></i>
<p>
<ul><li><strong>Croatia</strong> (as of May 31, 1996)
<li><strong>Delta</strong> 
<li><strong>USAir</strong> (as of June 1, 1996)
><li><strong>Air Mauritius</strong>  (as of July 1, 1996).
<li><strong>Qantas</strong>  (as of July 1, 1996).
<li><strong>Ansett Airlines</strong> (Australia)  (as of July 1, 1996).</ul>

<h3>Airlines with some smoke-free international flights:</h3>

<ul><li><strong>American Airlines</strong> banned smoking on flights to and from Europe, the Caribbean and to some destinations in Mexico as of June 1, 1996. It still permits smoking on its 3 daily flights to Japan.

<li><strong>British Airways</strong> bans smoking on 11 of their 19 flights between Britain and the US. The last flight of the day usually allows smoking.

<li><strong>Finnair flights</strong> to and from the US are 100% smokefree

<li><strong>Lufthansa German Airlines</strong> flights to and from the US are 100% smokefree 

<li><strong>Northwest </strong>allows smoking on 80% of flights to Asia.

<li><strong>Trans World Airlines</strong>' flights between the United States and France, Germany and the United Kingdom are 100% smokefree.

<li><strong>United Airlines</strong> banned smoking on flights across the Atlantic and within Europe except between Washington Dulles International Airport and Milan, Italy on June 1, 1996. United also banned smoking on trans-Pacific flights and those within Asia except certain flights to Tokyo.

<li><strong>CAAC</strong> (Civil Aviation Authority of China) bans smoking on domestic flights and some short international flights. For safety reasons, CAAC plans to extend a limited smoking ban to all international flights, due to at least one airline crash attributed to passenger smoking</ul>


<h3>Airlines Flying Internationally with smoking sections:</h3>

<ul><li>According to Travel Weekly the following airlines have smoking sections on all international flights: <strong>Aeroflot, Aerolineas Argentinas, Aeromexico, Air India, Alitalia, All Nippon Airways, CAAC (China), El Al, Finnair, Iberia, Japan Airlines, SAS, South African Airways, Swissair, Tower Air.  </strong>

<li>The  <strong>Concorde </strong> allows smoking on all its flights.
</ul>

