<a href=#aa1><center><h1>The Collaborators</h1></a>
Ads and collaborative promotions buy innocence-through-association, while ubiquity buys acceptance. Who disregards the health consequences of tobacco to assist in the addiction of a generation?

<p><i>I figure if it's really so bad for you, they wouldn't be selling them everywhere. I mean, you walk into Stop 'N' Go, and there's a whole wall of them right up front at the cash register. If they were really *that* bad for you, they'd make them less accessible.</i></p>

--18-year-old smoker, "Young, Carefree and in Love With Cigarettes," The New York Times,  July 30, 1995  </center></a></li>
