<HTML>


<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>

<TITLE>NR Soapbox-weekday</TITLE>


<CENTER><img src="/nationalreview/images/soap2.gif" ALT="NR Soapbox"></center>.

<P>
<!---------------------------------------------------------------->
<blockquote>

The NR Soapbox is a place where <I>NR Online</I> readers can voice their opinions regarding the major issues of the day. Respond to the question directly, or comment on previous responses. Please keep comments brief (100 words or fewer). The featured question will change at the end of each week; comments will be updated daily.</blockquote>
<P>
<center>This week's question is:</center>
<center><H1><I>What effect will Newt Gingrich's re-election have on the 105th Congress?</I></H1></center>


<br>
<center>To submit your comments,</center><br>
<center><A HREF="mailto:nronline@ix.netcom.com"><img src="/nationalreview/images/click2.gif" ALT="Click Here"></a>.<br></center>
<P>
Updated  1/13/97 
<HR>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------------------->


<P>
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------>
1/13/97<br>
Newt Gingrich's re-election as speaker of the House of Representatives will have little effect on the 105th Congress, which promises to be the most disappointing sequel since "Jaws 2." As Florence King pointed out in her recent public abandonment of the GOP, national Republicans lack the stones to lead this nation. What I would like Mr. Gingrich and his colleagues to answer is this: What is so alluring about Congress and the Beltway? Is it such a powerful tonic that you would willingly turn your backs on those of us who elected you? Or have you just become rabid Redskins fans?<br>
<I>Jim Conrey Carol Stream, Illinois, JConrey@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>
Since Newt will capitulate to the Democrats and liberal Republicans, the House will be more conciliatory to Billy Boy. The Senate is the last hope of conservatives. We in effect lost the House; if only Newt had not lost his fighting spirit and conservative principals. He should have talked less and acted more (ie; kick their butt, but don't talk about it).<br>
<I>Paul Oksnee, poksnee@netscape.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>
I think Newt is good for Congress, the Republican party, and America! One of can never be 100% sure of anything anybody else does, because we all "fall short of the Glory of God." Compared to so many people in and out of politics, Newt is an angel. I just wish the Republicans and Newt would be more proactive about undoing the damage the liberal establishment is doing. National Review is a great publication, and Rush is working hard to prove to the public that "evidence refutes liberalism," but most grassroots liberals have never heard of NR, and can't stand Rush. Newt's ideas about government and society line up with the ones our founding fathers had when they set out on the great democratic experiment. Now, if only we could get liberalism out of the schools and newspapers, and get people talking about Adam Smith and the Federalist Papers!<br>
<I>Ken Owsley, olympic@nas.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>


It will be hard to keep hitting Clinton for sleaze after the revelations about Newt. Newt's statement that it was the lawyers' fault seems lame as he is still using the lawyer and the lawyer says Newt read and approved everything he submitted. I don't blame Newt for a lot of the troubles he had. He was hemmed in by the new people he had made all hopped up when they were elected. They have learned some from the first term and should do a better job now.<br>
<I>JudgeDave@aol.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>

Newt's re-election provides a stabilizing influence on the Republican Revolution. If the Republican conference in the House was to switch leaders midstream, it would send a terrible message and cause much dissent. As for those few Republicans who voted against Newt because his leadership ability is supposedly weakened by ethics charges, do they not believe that members of a Speaker's own party walking away from him weakens his potential as a leader?<br>
<I>Jason D. Hall, Owensboro, KY, JDHallKY@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>


Newt is the greatest American since Reagan. I think all this B.S. about his so-called "wrongdoings" will blow over soon and be yesterday's news. Hell, we can't convict Wild Bill, you think that we can even talk about good ol' Newt? I claim no political party and consider myself neutral as far as the left and the right go. But the left needs to get with it: don't go accusing Newt of lining his pockets. All he did is teach a class at college that is one step above a community college. The man has a PhD in European history. If it was money he was interested in he would have went to a university, or better yet, a speaking tour. Lets all get over the petty stuff and start taking care of this great country again. Let's fix our budget (like every American family does), take care of our old people, and our poor people WHO CANNOT PROVIDE FOR THEMSELVES (not lazy people who refuse to work), and get on with being the greatest country in the world. Comments?<br> 
<I>chris</I> 
<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>


The OJ trial proved that there was no integrity left in the judicial system; now the re-election of Gingrich as House speaker shows us, if we didn't know already, that there is no integrity left in the legislative branch. We won't even discuss the executive branch.<br>
<I>Laura Patterson</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>

 Mr. Newt will have a revolutionary impact on the 105th Congress as he continues the revolution from the 104th. Long Live Speaker Newt. Let the cultural revolution begin.<br>
<I>James A. Hines, 74012.414@compuserve.com </I>
<hr>
<P>
1/13/97<br>


Newt has failed to follow his own standard of conduct for Speakers of the House; he should step down. If one shuts down the government because he rode in coach on Air Force One, and refuses to change the law that allows House members to utilize frequent-flyer mileage accrued on taxpayer trips for personal use, it would indeed be too much to expect him to step down. His book deal that he escaped discipline for profiting from could be added to you outrage list.<br>
<I>Daniel T. Howard, danh1@dth2.microserve.com</I>
<hr>
<hr>




<!---------------------------------------------------------------->


<center>To submit your comments,</center><br>
<center><A HREF="mailto:nronline@ix.netcom.com">click here</a>.</center>

