<html>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<title>Letter From Al -- January 27, 1997</title>
</head>
<body>
<p>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/topletr.gif" ALT="Letter From Al"></center>
<p>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/dear.gif"></center>
<P>
 <TABLE ALIGN=LEFT width=50%>
<TR>
<TH></TH>
<TD>                                                                





A few years ago, you asked me to help you out with your research in the Brazilian rainforest, and, as you'll remember, I said, ``Sure, no problem.''
<br>
So I cut you a check for my donation, and then I asked if maybe it would be possible to use some of the findings of your research in my soon-to-be-bestselling book, <U>Earth in the Balance</U>.
<br>
Now what I need to know is a) whether the check I wrote to you was a personal check; b) whether it was (more likely) a check drawn on the foundation I created with the money I had left over in my senatorial campaign war chest; and c) if it had ``for research'' in the memo section.<br>
I also need to know whether you and your research organization are a 501(c)(1), 501(c)(2), 501(c)(3), or 501(c)(4) corporation. <br>
I need all this pretty fast, by the way. At least by Sunday-morning talk-show hour.<br>
See, this thing with Gingrich is kind of unsettling. Don't get me wrong: I'm all for trying to undermine the guy. But I'm sure there's a more . . . how do I put this? . . . a more surgical way to get him.<br>
I wasn't really worried about it until Dad called. ``Gleetings, my number one son. How many Chinese businessmen have been in today?'' he said.<br>
``Cut it out, Dad,'' I groaned.<br>
``C'mon, Al! What'd they serve at lunch today in the mess? Moo Shu Pork? General Tsing Spicy Scallop?''<br>
``Dad, I'm hanging up the phone.''<br>
``It's a joke, boy! A joke! Lighten up!'' he cried. I could hear the ice rattle in his highball glass, which means he's finished his drink. Last week, I could hear the ice tinkling in a full glass, which meant I had to endure two whole verses of ``We Are Siamese if You Please,'' with Mom in the background banging a trash-can lid with a hammer, to simulate a gong.<br>
``Well it's not funny, Dad. In this first place, it's racially insensitive.''<br>
``Not as insensitive as fleecing those poor fellas to the tune of $300,000 for a five-minute White House sit-down and a doughnut.''<br>
``And we've given most of the money back.''<br>
Dad burst out laughing. ``I know! I read it in the paper! I mean, son, what are you running up there? A Chinese fire drill?''<br>
``Dad, I swear to God I'll hang up this phone.''<br>





</tr>
</TABLE>
<P>
<TABLE>
<tr>
<TH></TH>
<td>
``Simmer down, boy. You know, in my day, if we took three million dollars from a fellow, you'd better believe we'd keep it. Oh yes. And give him something for it, besides. Now I see you fellows on the news swearing up and down that all that money had absolutely no effect on policy. No effect on policy? Use your head, boy! Don't tell the customer that! If a man wants to pay three million dollars for a car, don't go on TV telling folks that it's okay, 'cause the car don't run. What are you, nuts?''<br>

``I'm not following your analogy,'' I said.<br>
``And then I read about this Gingrich character, and how he's in trouble because he used money from the wrong account to pay for a college course he was teaching. A college course! He didn't steal the money, or buy himself a Cadillac, or send his girlfriend to Hawaii. No. He taught a college course.''<br>
``Dad, I have to go.''<br>
``How do you trust a man like that? How can you trust a man who doesn't take a little for himself?''<br>
``Dad, I'm late for a meeting.''<br>
``Well, you just watch out. You guys in D.C. have so many tax laws and ethics investigations you've turned everyone into a crook.''<br>
``Bye, Dad.'' And I hung up. But Dad's point is well taken: I've got to start cleaning up some loose ends before the '00 campaign starts in earnest.<br>
I called up David Bonior. He's spearheading the battle against Newt, so I figured that he's an expert.<br>
``Hmmmm,'' he said, after I had laid out the situation. ``This doesn't look good!''<br>
``It doesn't? But isn't it, at most, just a technical mistake? A minor oversight?'' I asked.<br>
``Ooohhh no no no. This kind of malfeasance -- ''<br>
``Excuse me. Isn't malfeasance kind of strong?''<br>
``Call it what you will, sir. But it's a Gingrich-sized oversight. The good news, if you're interested, is that Dick Gephardt has some similar, though slightly more serious, problems.''<br>
``Well, I appreciate that, David, but I really think we've all gone too far with these rigidly picky ethics attacks for purely personal gain.''<br>
Bonior clucked his tongue. ``Spoken,'' he said, ``like someone who has some serious violations of the tax code to explain.''<br>
``Oh, come on, David,'' I said. ``Everyone has a few mistakes on the books.''<br>
``Not me,'' he said. ``See you in New Hampshire.''<br>
So, please, Rusty, hurry up with those receipts!

</TD>
</tr>
</TABLE>

