<H2> <CENTER><I>National Review </I></H2>

<HR WIDTH=30%>
<BR>Below is a small sampling of the contents of the 10 July 1995 issue of National
Review.<BR><BR>

</CENTER><UL>

 <LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/10july95/drugs.html">Legalizing Drugs:
 Just Say Yes</A><BR>
 <I>National Review</I> interviews Michael S. Gazzaniga who argues that society
 will be better off if it quits the drug war, and experiments with
 legalization......Ethan Nadelmann checks on the Swiss experiment of selling
 heroin to addicts.
 <P>
 <LI>Inventing
 Anti-Semitism</A></BR>
 Some Jews have expressed concern about growing anti-Semitism in America; but
 Richard John Neuhaus suggests that it is not anti-Semitism which is on the
 rise, but rather anti-liberalsim.
 <P>
 <LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/10july95/gimlet.html">The Gimlet Eye</A><BR>
 Andrew Ferguson discovers that in Washington, nothing succeeds like failure.
 <P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/10july95/theweek.html">The Week</A>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/10july95/rusty.html">Letter from Al</A>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR> 
